 LONDON, Sept 8 (bdnews24.com/Reuters) - England clinched the one-day international series against India on Saturday with a seven-wicket victory in the seventh and final match at Lord's. India had levelled the series at 3-3 with wins at Headingley and at the Oval but their hopes of a remarkable comeback evaporated as they were bowled out for 187 after captain Rahul Dravid won the toss and elected to bat. England lost both openers for ducks to raise the hopes of a huge Indian contingent in a sell-out crowd but Ian Bell (36) and unbeaten half centuries from Kevin Pietersen (71) and Paul Collingwood (64) guided them home with 13 overs to spare. Andrew Flintoff, who returned to the England side after passing a fitness test on his troublesome ankle, and Dimitri Mascarenhas both took three wickets in the India innings. England won the series 4-3, making up for their 1-0 loss in the three-match Test series against the tour
